📝 My summary of the week, which passed under the slogan:
"We're beating work-life balance with sticks."

😵 Work and mood
There was too much work. At the same time, I was struggling with my own mood. It's been several weeks since I stopped taking antidepressants. Theoretically, the withdrawal effects should wear off (usually within four weeks), but my mood still fluctuates.
One day, I woke up irritable. An hour later, I'm sitting there, petting the cat, saying some kind words to her... and I catch myself welling up with tears.

Then, during the day, I'm knocked out from fatigue, and in the evening, on the contrary, it's hard to fall asleep, so I keep working on my tasks.

Hormonal swings are more severe when rest is cut off from the schedule. A note for the future.

🏃 Preparing for a half marathon
I'm continuing to run and gradually realized something important:
my muscle problems weren't so much due to technique, but rather to warm-up, recovery, and... shoes.
And not just my running shoes, but my everyday shoes as well.

Because of the wrong shoes, my muscles were constantly overloaded. I changed my street shoes and immediately felt the difference. At the same time, I switched to HOKA running shoes, and the results became even more noticeable.

Now I'm comfortably maintaining a training pace of about 5:00 over the distance.
Details and small details greatly influence the process and results in running.

🏊 About rest and reality
On Sunday, I planned to do interval training and the pool. In the end, I woke up at 12 and realized that my limit was easy swimming.
And I wanted to try out new swimming trunks – after the beach shorts I used to swim in (the difference is noticeable).
Next, I want to get goggles and a cap for different swimming styles.

📖 On rest as a choice
Sometimes the best plan is to admit you need rest. So I'm chilling, sitting in a cafe, and reading The Lord of the Rings in the original.

💻 On IT
We're currently in intensive preparation for new projects. Much is still under wraps, but the workload is huge.

🤖 AI and Development
One interesting thing is that I've started actively working with AI for app creation.
I'm not a developer, but I have a strong foundation in mobile apps: understanding where things break, what edge cases there are, and what's important to consider.

What used to take 4-5 months of team development and significant budgets can now be done much faster. Yes, with some caveats regarding the level and detail. But we don't always need Google-level polish.

⚡ Awareness of Change
And this is both inspiring... and a little scary.

We're already living in a world where the need for large numbers of developers and technicians is beginning to reevaluate.
The role of specialists is changing. Requirements are changing. Incomes are shifting.

I see this from within the industry, and it's impossible to ignore.

🎧 Thoughts on the Future
The other day, I generated an AI podcast based on two large legal documents about the future of the economy and listened to it. I'm using something I'm a bit afraid of, yeah.

There are some utopian moments in the material.
But the overall direction is clear: the world is changing. And the question is no longer whether it will happen, but how we will adapt to it.
